</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/0f0794724f011ef10115db4e68dd02006a6325a7" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -1.838ex; width:10.477ex; height:5.343ex;" alt="{\displaystyle A_{n}\sim {\frac {c\lambda ^{n}}{n}}}"></span></dd></dl>
<p>where <i>λ</i> = 4.0626 and <i>c</i> = 0.3169.<sup id="cite&#95;ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25"><span class="cite-bracket">&#91;</span>25<span class="cite-bracket">&#93;</span></a></sup> However, this result is not proven and the values of <i>λ</i> and <i>c</i> are only estimates.
</p><p>The known theoretical results are not nearly as specific as this estimate. It has been proven that
</p>
<dl><dd><span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle \lim _{n\rightarrow \infty }(A_{n})^{\frac {1}{n}}=\lambda }">
